#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:7
msgid ""
"In YunoHost permission management web admin interface, you can specify which "
"user can access your system through SFTP."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:11
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Go to : \n"
"- Groups and permissions > Individual user permissions. \n"
"- Click on add a permission and select SFTP\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:13
msgid ""
"However, those user are chrooted in their home directory for security "
"reasons."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:15
msgid ""
"If you want to give access to a specific apps through SFTP, here are "
"additional steps to do after giving the SFTP permission in the web interface."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:19
msgid ""
"In instructions below, - USER is the user to whom you wish to give "
"permission to edit wordpress files.  - `/var/www/wordpress/wp-config.php` "
"must be replaced by the path your app config file. For example, for yeswiki "
"(`/var/www/yeswiki/wakka.config.php`)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:20
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mkdir -p /home/USER/apps/wordpress\n"
"touch /home/USER/.nobackup\n"
"mount --bind /var/www/wordpress /home/USER/apps/wordpress\n"
"echo \"/var/www/wordpress /home/USER/apps/wordpress none defaults,bind 0 0\" >> /etc/fstab\n"
"find /var/www/wordpress -type d -exec chmod g+s {} \\;\n"
"\n"
"setfacl -R -m u:wordpress:rwX /var/www/wordpress\n"
"setfacl -R -d -m u:wordpress:rwX /var/www/wordpress\n"
"setfacl -m u:wordpress:r-- /var/www/wordpress/wp-config.php\n"
"\n"
"setfacl -R -m u:USER:rwX /var/www/wordpress\n"
"setfacl -R -d -m u:USER:rwX /var/www/wordpress\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: docs/admin/45.tutorials/65.sftp_on_apps.mdx:38
msgid ""
"Quick commands explanation : - `mkdir -p /PATH` creates a folder in the "
"specified PATH - `touch` creates an empty file - `mount --bind` makes the "
"contents of the source file or directory available at the target location "
"without actually moving or copying the data.  - `setfacl` set the file "
"permissions"
msgstr ""
